Easy, inexpensive and beautiful! 

I didn’t want large orange slices. I wanted something smaller that would accent the tree without taking over. 

I love the bronze-y look of the limes so I did both limes and mandarin oranges. 

Easy Instructions

- Preheat oven to 200°
- Slice citrus into 1/4” slices. 
- Place on a rack on a cookie sheet. (If you don’t have a rack, use parchment paper.
- Cook at 200° for 4 - 6 hours. 

Tie with twine and hang!

1, 2, 3 or 4? Which one is your favorite? 

I love a beautifully set table. It always signifies something special is happening. 

It takes me straight back to the two times a year when we all came together to celebrate as a family. Thanksgiving and Christmas.

My grandmother would get out her china and fine silver and everyone, for a few hours, would be on their best behavior. 

To know my family is to know “best behavior” was a rarity. I cherish those moments. 

They typically ended with an argument and a door slam, but hey … we had a few hours with a beautiful table scape first.

Homemade chicken broth recipe ⬇️
is simple to make and a game changer for any soup!

TO DO: 
1. Find this recipe and all our soup recipes at jjandstefanie.com. 
2. Hover over RECIPES in the top bar.
3. Click Soups and Salads. 
4. ENJOY!

INGREDIENTS
* 2 chicken carcasses
* 2 celery ribs with leaves, cut into chunks
* 2 medium carrots, cut into chunks
* 2 medium onions, quartered
* 12 garlic cloves
* 2 bay leaves
* 1/2 teaspoon dried rosemary
* 1/2 teaspoon dried thyme
* 1/2 teaspoon dried oregano
* 10 - 12 whole peppercorns
* 4 quarts water 

This homemade chicken bone broth recipe made with fresh vegetables and herbs is the perfect base for your next soup. 

You can also use it to make casseroles, add flavor to rice or any recipe that calls for chicken broth.

Kitchen Towel Storage Hack

2. Keep a basket below where you toss your dirty towels until you are ready to do a load. 

3. I only buy white flour sack towels because you can bleach the stains out.  We use them in lieu of paper towels as often as possible.

This is a doozy of an update I never thought I would ever write.

Last week I went in for my annual physical. In preparation for that physical I had all my blood work drawn on Monday and was to meet with my doctor on Friday. 

On Tuesday evening, while at dinner, my doctor called and I walked outside to take the call. In a kind voice, she got straight to the point, “Your blood levels are off and there’s no easy way to say this, I think you have leukemia.” 

There are no words to describe the shock or the inability to find any word that rhymes with leukemia. 

I was at dinner with my 17 yo Colt and his friend and mother so I calmly told the doctor I would call her back, walked back into the restaurant like nothing had happened, finished the meal and then drove home to JJ. 

We called the doctor back together and she explained that she had everything set up for us the next morning to show up at the hospital. No need to go tonight, stay home and get some sleep. 

I stayed home, I did not sleep. “What mimics leukemia in blood work I googled over and over.” 

Wednesday morning within a couple of hours of arriving at the hospital it was confirmed. 

I have leukemia. 

We are choosing to call it Over Achieving White Blood Cells because that’s way cooler sounding and less terrifying.

My outlook is good. The doctors assure me I will be fine. It will be a battle, one we are calling The Storm. We are ready. 

The love, the support, the prayers, the hilarious and heartfelt texts have my strength buckets overflowing. 

I am in battle mode. 
I am in gratitude mode. 

I don’t know why this is for us to walk through, but we are ready with strength, humor and fierce determination. 

The content will look a little different around here over the next 6ish months. We will still be talking about remodeling, design and food but we will be sprinkling in updates along the way. 

Please feel free to reach out and know I will respond as often as possible to your DMs or comments. They will be filling my tank along the journey!

More to come soon about donating blood and getting your annual checkups but we will ease into that. ❤️

The kids @pacificridgeschool get to paint their senior parking spaces. @colt_mullen has struggled trying to figure out what he wanted to do. One of his fabulous smiley face sketches that he leaves all over our house maybe? We talked and talked about it and could never figure out the right thing. 

Life figured it out for him.

It’s brought me to tears every time I’ve look at it today.  It’s so sweet. So perfect. So strong. 

This should not be his life right now, but it unfortunately is. 

My 3 boys and my husband are my rock! They get me through the rough moments right now giving me the strength to say to myself over and over all day long … “I can do hard things. And I can do them well.” #stefstrong

I’m Home! 

After a long 30 days in the hospital, I am bald, 20 ponds lighter (not the diet i was hoping for) happy and home for 10 - 14 days to recover and regroup before my next round of treatments. 

And while Otis exists in a constant state of RBF this dog was beyond excited to reunite with me! (Scroll through to the video, sound on.)

My first treatment was a beast, but it did its job and put me in remission. 

These next few treatments are meant to keep me there while I wait for a bone marrow transplant. The first step is to find the right donor. They tell me that could take a couple of months as they search the database of donors for a good match. 

I am working on a blog explaining how to become a potential donor of your bone marrow which can literally save someone’s life via BeTheMatch (and render you an instant superhero) as well as the importance of donating blood. 

Fun Fact: I had 25 platelet infusions and 15 blood transfusions after my first round of chemo. Watching those lifesaving bags drip into my body to keep me alive and knowing there were people out there who selflessly gave those to me was life changing. Gratitude isn’t a big enough word. I am alive because of them. 

In the meantime, I am home. I hugged my children, I slept next to JJ, Otis has been snuggled up next to me since I walked through the door. 

I watched the hot air balloons rise last evening from my patio, I stared at my garden with joy. I will be cooking in my kitchen this weekend, watching football with my family and dogs. Go Colts (please suck a little less this year). I am surrounded by all the things I love and I am grateful. So very grateful. 

Thank you all for the messages, texts, cards, gifts, funny memes, meals that show up at our door, prayers, support and love. It all made me feel so safe and strong. While I fought the rest of you were holding me up, the net under me, never letting me fall too far. Thank you isn’t enough but it’s all I have. 

I am starting to work again so this feed will start to get back to some of the beautiful distractions life has to offer in the form of comforting food and making your house a place you can’t wait to come home to.

The first photo is me a few months ago. The second is me now. 

On August 15th I was diagnosed with leukemia. 

You can see more of the story by scrolling back a few posts. 

So many of you have asked how you can help. My simple answer is SIGN UP TO BE A BONE MARROW DONOR. 

You can literally become a real life superhero and save someone’s life. 

Not a movie superhero who throws cars and fights crime, though that’s pretty cool. 

You will be the best kind of hero … a real life human will get to live because you said yes kind of superhero. 

It’s easy! 
Click the link in bio. 
Order a kit. 
Swab.
Return. 

When someone in need matches you, you will get a call that it’s your turn to save a life. 

You have to be between the ages of 18 & 40. BUT don’t be discouraged my friends born in the 60s and 70s, you can still help by sharing this post!

OR sending the link to any young people you know. 

Link in bio or DM me or comment DONOR and and I will send it to you! I’ll make it easy!

Check out all the amazing stories of donors and children and adults in need on @bethematch

Tonight I’m soaking it all in and feeling so much gratitude for an amazing young man who decided to register to be a stem cell donor. 

Tomorrow I start the process of receiving the greatest Christmas present anyone could ever ask for. 

Looking forward to being back here in a month-ish enjoying the holidays with my family. The gifts are all wrapped and the house is decorated. All that’s left to do is climb this mountain and come home and relax and heal with my family. 

In the meantime, feel free to send me your favorite funniest memes, inspirational quotes and just a quick hello. I love hearing from you all. It lifts my spirits and gives me strength. ❤️

#christmasdecor #christmasdiy

Counting the days until I am sitting in my living room celebrating Christmas with JJ, my boys, Otis & Lola. ❤️🐶🐕

I received my stem cell transplant on Tuesday. Two bags from a complete stranger who selflessly took time out of his life to give me mine back. How does one ever show enough gratitude? 

Everything is going well. I had my last chemo treatment yesterday and now we move into the phase of managing how my new stem cells and my body play nicely together. 

We are still climbing a mountain, but we are passing through some amazing checkpoints. 

Thank you to ALL of you who continue to reach out and support us. The texts, DMs, cards, gifts AND THE MEALS that show up several times a week to feed my family, while I can’t, have brought us so much joy and gratitude. Again, how does one ever show enough gratitude? I plan on spending a few more decades here trying!

Thank you for keeping our hearts, bellies and spirits lifted over the last several months.❤️❤️❤️

The plan is to be home mid-December. We will continue to update you … in between holiday posts of course. You can take the girl out of her Christmas home (temporarily) but you can’t take the Christmas home out of her heart! 🎄 

Please feel free to reach out anytime! We love hearing from you!
